Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Domain:¶

Civil engineering

Data:¶

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Concrete+Compressive+Strength

Description:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Attributes Information:¶

Name Data Type Measurement Description
1. Cement (cement) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
2. Blast Furnace Slag (slag) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
3. Fly Ash (ash) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
4. Water(water) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
5. Superplasticizer (superplastic) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
6. Coarse Aggregate (coarseagg) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
7. Fine Aggregate (fineagg) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
8. Age(age) quantitative Day (1~365) Input Variable
9. Concrete compressive strength(strength) quantitative MPa Output Variable

Objective:¶

Is to predict the compressive strength of concrete. Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%.

Steps and tasks¶

  1. Libraries & Dataset Import
  2. EDA
    1. Univariate Analysis
    2. Bivariate Analysis
    3. Feature Engineering
      1. Dealing with the Outliers
      2. Slag, Ash, Superplastic - Binarization

def display_num_stat_graph(data, col, hist_color='seagreen', hist_mean='tomato', hist_median='steelblue', box_color='steelblue'):
    f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    gs = f.add_gridspec(1, 2)

    with sns.axes_style("whitegrid"):
        ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 0])
        sns.distplot(data[col], color=hist_color, kde=True, rug=True)
        ax.axvline(data[col].mean(), color = hist_mean, label='Mean')
        ax.axvline(data[col].median(), color = hist_median, label='Median')
        ax.legend()

    with sns.axes_style("darkgrid"):
        ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 1])
        sns.boxplot(x=data[col], notch = True, whis = 1.5, color=box_color)
    
    f.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
def printc(text, color):
    colors = {
        'black':'\033[30m',
        'red':'\033[31m',
        'green':'\033[32m',
        'orange':'\033[33m',
        'blue':'\033[34m',
        'purple':'\033[35m',
        'cyan':'\033[36m',
        'lightgrey':'\033[37m',
        'darkgrey':'\033[90m',
        'lightred':'\033[91m',
        'lightgreen':'\033[92m',
        'yellow':'\033[93m',
        'lightblue':'\033[94m',
        'pink':'\033[95m',
        'lightcyan':'\033[96m'
    }
    style = {
        'reset':'\033[0m',
        'bold':'\033[01m'
    }
    
    print(colors[color], text, style['reset'])
        

def display_num_skew_outliers(data, col):
    # Computing IQR
    Q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    LowerWhisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    MinValue = data[col].min()
    UpperWhisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    MaxValue = data[col].max()
    
    # Update whiskers
    LowerWhisker = max(MinValue, LowerWhisker)
    UpperWhisker = min(MaxValue, UpperWhisker)
    
    # Outliers
    LowerOutliers = data[data[col] < LowerWhisker][col]   
    LowerOutliersCount = LowerOutliers.count()
    UpperOutliers = data[data[col] > UpperWhisker][col]
    UpperOutliersCount = UpperOutliers.count()

    print('>', col.title())
    printc('Mean         : {}'.format(data[col].mean()), 'red') 
    printc('Median       : {}'.format(data[col].median()), 'blue') 
    print('Skew          :', data[col].skew())
    print('Lower whisker :', LowerWhisker)
    print('Upper whisker :', UpperWhisker)

    print('Outliers above upper whisker: ', UpperOutliersCount, '({:.1f}%)'.format( (UpperOutliersCount/data.shape[0])*100) )
    if(UpperOutliersCount > 0):
        print('  > (closest 15):', ', '.join(map(str, UpperOutliers.head(15))))
    
    print('Outliers under lower whisker: ', LowerOutliersCount, '({:.1f}%)'.format( (LowerOutliersCount/data.shape[0])*100) )
    if(LowerOutliersCount > 0):
        print('  > (closest 15):', ', '.join(map(str, LowerOutliers.head(15))))
    
def plot_counts_percentages(data, col, vr=0):
    total_clients = data.shape[0]
    chart = sns.countplot(data[col], order = data[col].value_counts().index, palette='muted');
    chart.set(title=col.title(), xlabel='', ylabel='Count')
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(),  rotation=vr)
    for p in chart.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        chart.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 3, '{:1.2f}'.format((height/total_clients)*100), ha='center')

def treat_outliers(series, fix_strategy='median', detect_strategy='IQR'):
    lower = 0
    upper = 0
    s = series.copy()

    # Detection
    if(detect_strategy == 'IQR'):
        Q1 = s.quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = s.quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    elif(detect_strategy == 'CAPPING'):
        mean = s.mean()
        std = s.std()
        lower = mean - 2 * std
        upper = mean + 2 * std
    else:
         raise Exception(f'Unknown detect_strate "{detect_strategy}"')
    
    # Replacement
    if(fix_strategy == 'median'):
        median = s.median()
        s[(s < lower) | (s > upper)] = median
    elif(fix_strategy == 'mean'):
        mean = series.mean()
        s[(s < lower) | (s > upper)] = mean
    elif(fix_strategy == 'capping'):
        s[s < lower] = lower
        s[s > upper] = upper
    else:
         raise Exception(f'Unknown fix_strategy "{fix_strategy}"')
    
    return s

def boxplot_grid(data, columns, nrows, ncols):
    plt.figure(figsize=(17,15))
    index = 1
    for col in columns:
        with sns.axes_style("darkgrid"):
            plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, index)
            sns.boxplot(data[col], notch = True, whis = 1.5, color='steelblue')
        index += 1
    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

seed = 33

def get_percentage(df, subset):
    return len(subset)/len(df.index) * 100

def adjusted_r_squared(est, pX, py):
    r2 = est.score(pX, py)  # should be R2 score
    return 1 - (1 - r2) * (len(py) - 1) / (len(py) - pX.shape[1] - 1)

def reg_metrics(est, pX_train, pX_test, py_train, py_test):
    # R-squared 
    # the coefficient of determination. It is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable/explained.
    # R^2 is not a reliable metric as it always increases with addition of more attributes even if the attributes have no 
    # influence on the predicted variable.
    #
    # Adj. R-squared
    # is the modified form of R-squared adjusted for the number of independent variables in the model.
    
    py_pred = est.predict(pX_test)
    r2_train = est.score(pX_train, py_train)
    r2_test = est.score(pX_test, py_test)
    adj_r2_train = adjusted_r_squared(est, pX_train, py_train)
    adj_r2_test = adjusted_r_squared(est, pX_test, py_test)
    
    return {'r2_train': r2_train,
        'r2_test': r2_test,
        'r2_delta': abs(r2_train - r2_test),
        'r2_test_v2': r2_score(py_test, py_pred),
        'adj_r2_train': adj_r2_train,
        'adj_r2_test': adj_r2_test,
        'adj_r2_delta': abs(adj_r2_train - adj_r2_test),
        'RMSE_test': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(py_test, py_pred)) 
    }

def calc_ci95(scores):
    mean = scores.mean()
    std = scores.std()
    z_025 = 1.96   # critical value, a/2 = 0.5/2 = 0.025
    
    lower = mean - z_025 * std / np.sqrt(len(scores))
    upper = mean + z_025 * std / np.sqrt(len(scores))
    return (lower, upper)

def calc_percentile_95_range(scores):
    alpha = 0.95                             # for 95% confidence 
    p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100              # tail regions on right and left .25 on each side indicated by P value (border)
    lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(scores, p))  
    p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
    upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(scores, p))
   
    return (lower, upper)
 
def kfold_metrics(estimator, pX_train, py_train, num_folds=10, scoring=None):
        cv_alg = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed)
        
        # Options for scoring:
        # - 'neg_root_mean_squared_error' for metrics.mean_squared_error
        # - 'r2' for metrics.r2_score
        # - or a scorer callable object / function with signature scorer(estimator, X, y) which should return only a single value.
        scoring_method = 'r2'
        if(scoring == 'adj_r2'):
            scoring_method = adjusted_r_squared
            
        scores = cross_val_score(estimator, pX_train, py_train, cv=cv_alg, scoring=scoring_method) 

        return {
            'count': len(scores),
            'mean': scores.mean(),
            'std': scores.std(),
            'ci95': calc_ci95(scores),
            'percentile95': calc_percentile_95_range(scores)
        }


def get_reg_report(metrics, title, kfold_scoring):
    return pd.DataFrame(
        [[
            metrics["r2_train"],
            metrics["r2_test"],
            metrics["r2_delta"],
            metrics["adj_r2_train"],
            metrics["adj_r2_test"],
            metrics["adj_r2_delta"],
            f'{metrics["mean"]:.4f} \u00B1 {metrics["std"]:.2f}',
            f'{metrics["ci95"][0]:.4f} - {metrics["ci95"][1]:.4f}',
            f'{metrics["percentile95"][0]:.4f} - {metrics["percentile95"][1]:.4f}',
            metrics["RMSE_test"]]],
        columns=[
            'R\u00B2 train',
            'R\u00B2 test',
            '\u0394 R\u00B2',
            'Adj.R\u00B2 train',
            'Adj.R\u00B2 test',
            '\u0394 Adj.R\u00B2',
            'KFold Adj.R\u00B2 CV' if kfold_scoring == 'adj_r2' else 'KFold R\u00B2',
            'ci95 CV',
            'class95 CV',
            'RSME test'
        ],
        index=[title]
    )

def print_fi_coeff(est, pX_train):
    coeff = []
    if hasattr(est, 'feature_importances_'):
        coeff = est.feature_importances_
    elif hasattr(est, 'coef_'):
        coeff = abs(est.coef_)

    if len(coeff) > 0:
        fi_df = pd.DataFrame(coeff, columns = ['Importance'], index = pX_train.columns).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False).reset_index()
        fi_df.rename(columns = {'index': 'Feature'}, inplace=True)
        display(fi_df)

from xgboost.sklearn import XGBRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    
def estimator_factory(estimator):
    if(estimator == 'LinearRegression'):
        return LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    elif(estimator == 'Lasso'):
        return Lasso(random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'Ridge'):
        return Ridge(random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'KNeighborsRegressor'):
        return KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=4)
    elif(estimator == 'SVR'):
        return SVR(C=6000, epsilon=0.0001)
    elif(estimator == 'DecisionTreeRegressor'):
        return DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion='friedman_mse', max_depth=19, min_samples_split=6, max_features=None, random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'RandomForestRegressor'):
        return RandomForestRegressor(random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'BaggingRegressor'):
        return BaggingRegressor(random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'GradientBoostingRegressor'):
        return GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'AdaBoostRegressor'):
        return AdaBoostRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=seed)
    elif(estimator == 'XGBRegressor'):
        return XGBRegressor(objective ='reg:squarederror', n_estimators = 90, max_depth=5, eta=0.32, subsample=1, colsample_bytree=1, seed=seed) 
    else:
         raise Exception(f'Unknown estimator "{estimator}"')
            
def run_estimators(data, estimators, options={'kfold':'r2'}):
    X = data.drop('strength', axis=1)
    Y = data['strength']
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.30, random_state=seed)
    reports=[]

    for estimator_name in estimators:
        if type(estimator_name) is dict:
            estimator = estimator_name['regressor']
            title = estimator_name['title']
        else:
            if 'pipe_factory' in options:
                pipe_factory = options['pipe_factory']
                estimator = pipe_factory(estimator_factory(estimator_name))
                title = f'{estimator_name}_{options["pipe_name"]}'
            else:
                estimator = estimator_factory(estimator_name)
                title = f'{estimator_name}_{options["suff"]}' if 'suff' in options else estimator_name
            
        estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)
        m1 = reg_metrics(estimator, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)
        m2 = kfold_metrics(estimator, X, Y, scoring=options['kfold'])
        metrics = {**m1, **m2}
        reports.append(get_reg_report(metrics, title, kfold_scoring=options['kfold']))
    
    return pd.concat(reports, sort=False)

def run_custom_estimators(estimator, pX, pY, pX_train, pX_test, py_train, py_test, title, options={'kfold':'r2'}):
    estimator.fit(pX_train, py_train)
    m1 = reg_metrics(estimator, pX_train, pX_test, py_train, py_test)
    m2 = kfold_metrics(estimator, pX, pY, scoring=options['kfold'])
    metrics = {**m1, **m2}
    
    return get_reg_report(metrics, title, kfold_scoring=options['kfold'])

Slag, Ash, Superplastic - Binarization¶

As we saw in our previous analysis, all these 3 attributes have double Gausians. This is because these aggregates are actually optional components for the concrete. Many rows in out data set have them as 0.

Let's try and introduce binary attributes which will indicate if a particular component is in or out. Also we can try creating an aggregate attribute which indicates which of 3 components is in the mix.

In order to validate the results we will run a set of basic regressors as we did earlier for outliers.

Age vs Strength¶

As we know already we have several measures taken for the same concrete mixture at different moments in time (age). So let us plot age/strength graphs for the mixtures with enough samples.

Just to limit the number of items to show, we will print first 10 charts which have more than 4 age samples, that have no several samples for the same age and max age < 300.

In [160]:
tdf = df.drop_duplicates(inplace=False, keep='first')
res = tdf.groupby(['cement', 'slag', 'ash', 'water', 'superplastic', 'coarseagg', 'fineagg'])

f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(20, 6))

count=10
for key, gdf in res:
    p_count = len(gdf)
    
    if(p_count > 4 and len(gdf['age'].unique()) == p_count and gdf['age'].max() < 300):
        gdf_sorted = gdf.sort_values(by='age', ascending=False)
        temp_gdf = gdf_sorted.reset_index()
        ratio = (temp_gdf['water']/temp_gdf['cement'])[0];
        
        ax.plot(gdf_sorted['age'], gdf_sorted['strength'], marker='o', linewidth=2, markersize=8, label=f'{ratio:.04f}', linestyle="-")
        count -= 1
        if(count == 0):
            break

ax.legend()
ax.set_title('Age vs Strength')
ax.set_xlabel('Age')
ax.set_ylabel('Strength')
plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='both', labelsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Insights:

  • Now we can see that there is a definite mathematical equesion between age and strength. Concrete becomes stronger with time.
  • Also by looking at that orange, green and blue lines (second chart) we can notice that for the same age they have several values of strength, this indicates that the same type of concrete mixture was tested in different times/places with a little bit different outcome results. These kind of cases can be easily detaced and addressed. However there can be cases when ages do not repeat but it is still a mix from different places/times (see green line on the first chart), this kind is not easily detectable.
  • If we knew the formula (looks like a logarithmic equation) that can become a very good predictor. We can use this knowledge to expand our dataset on missging ages, so we can generate more data based of math formula, which should defenetely help our models. But this thechnique will reqiure more time to implement correctly, so we should see first if it is worth the time spent. Plus there some issues to overcome. Firstly we don't have any attribute which can help us to separate same mixtures with different results. Secondly there are other unknown factors that move those lines up and down on the strength axis.

Polynomial Features, PCA, Scaling and Transformations¶

Now we will investigate transformations that should really come together. Let us try out different combinations of common and custom transformers. We will also use different feature sets for different algorithms as not all of them benefit from the same features.

We will see if transformations like StandardScaler can help us in any way. Traditionally we would use scalers to normalize attributes that use different scales and ranges. In our case, all concrete components are measured in the same way, and only age stands apart.

Also, it is very important to note one thing. If before we could apply changes across the whole dataset, now we should be very careful not to create test data leaks as these transformations will use mean/median/std, etc obtained using all provided data and so knowledge of the test set will leak into the train set. In order to avoid this kind of mistake, we will employ pipelines to achieve consistency and apply transformations separately to training and test sets.

After multiple experiments the best combinations are as following:

In [179]:
special_features = ['cement']
numeric_features = ['slag', 'ash', 'water', 'superplastic', 'coarseagg', 'fineagg', 'age', 'w/c']
no_tranform_features = ['age_cat']

def pipe_factory_LOG_SS(regressor):
    concrete_scaler_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('log1p',  FunctionTransformer(np.log1p, validate=True)),
        ('scaler', StandardScaler())
    ])
    
    preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
        transformers=[
            ('special', concrete_scaler_transformer, special_features),
            ('num', StandardScaler(), numeric_features),
            ('passthrough', 'passthrough', no_tranform_features)
        ])

    return Pipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('regressor',  regressor)
    ])

  • As it is reqired by the project objective we need to pick 1 boosting and 1 bagging algorithms, luckly we have BaggingRegressor and GradientBoostingRegressor / XGBRegressor in out top 5. Hence in the next section we will try to tune hyper parameters for our leaders.

        ('regressor',  regressor)
    ])

gb_best_params = {'criterion': 'friedman_mse', 'learning_rate': 0.1, 'loss': 'ls', 'max_depth': 3, 'max_features': 6, 'min_impurity_decrease': 0.2, 'min_samples_leaf': 10, 'min_samples_split': 10, 'n_estimators': 485, 'subsample': 0.3}
gb_best_params['random_state'] = seed

regressor = GradientBoostingRegressor(**gb_best_params)

report_f_gb = run_custom_estimators(regressor, X, Y, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, 'GradientBoostingRegressor', options={'kfold':'adj_r2'})
display(report_f_gb)

Conclusions¶

  • As we are probably expected from the very beginning XGBRegressor gave us the best results. R² 0.9480, Adj.R² 0.9452, KFold CV with Adj.R² as the scorrer 0.9345 ± 0.02, 95% CI [0.9234 - 0.9456] and the metric form the calass for 95% of results is [0.9013 - 0.9589]. Also we got very low RSME 3.7869.
  • Bagging regressors may seem to overfit on a single run, however simulation using KFold CV shows good average scores.
  • Overall it was an interesting work. We did uni/bi-variate analysis, we had a deep go at EDA and Feature Engineering and created new features, selected features per each model, used PCA, PolynomialFeatures, scalers/transformers etc. and finally produced models which are considerably better for all basic regressors. As the final step we picked best 4 models and performed hyper parameters tuning for each model.
  • Further optimization is possible with GridSearchCV where we could tune hyper parameters that we got from RandomizedSearchCV even more by using a smaller steps around the values.
  • In this research we decided to be conservative and used Adj.R² as our main validation metric. However we also collected R², KFold Adj.R² CV, 95% CI, RSME etc. to support our findings.
  • One of the important features that we used is pipelines. They are invaluable when it comes to preventing data leaks and minimizing human error.
  • Convinient Summary dataframes/sections were also provided for the ease of reading.
